{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"34dc6f97-a99b-4052-b559-c884895610f1","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\n### Analyzing a .NET crash dump\n\n**Recommended tools:**\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform, easiest)\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump   # if not installed\n   dotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n   ```\n   Then inside the REPL:\n   - `clrstack` — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n   - `pe` — print the last exception\n   - `dumpheap -stat` — heap overview\n   - `threads` — list all threads\n   - `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect other threads\n\n2. **Visual Studio** (Windows) — open the `.dmp` directly, click \"Debug with Managed Only\"\n\n3. **`lldb` + SOS** (Linux/macOS) — for mixed native/managed analysis\n\n### Quick triage steps\n```\n$ dotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n> pe              # shows the exception that caused the crash\n> clrstack        # shows the stack trace\n```\n\nThe `pe` (print exception) output will typically point you straight to the root cause — exception type, message, and stack trace.\n\nWould you like help running any of these commands on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8c8091f6-6df8-4080-ae64-e8362413a7d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description specifically says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\" So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":445,"requestId":"C3DA:1EBA3E:1C1ED83:1FBC09C:6A07C3AD"},"id":"9d8ac488-e434-4944-8167-575634e3df90","timestamp":"2026-05-16